Dialogue: 0,0:00:00.30,0:00:04.70,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}١ ألف لام را\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}1. Alif-Lam-Ra.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:05.00,0:00:08.98,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}تلك آيات الكتاب المبين\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}These are the verses of the clear Book.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:09.28,0:00:16.74,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٢ إنا أنزلناه قرآنا عربيا لعلكم تعقلون\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}2. Indeed, We have sent it down as an Arabic Quran\Nso that you may understand.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:17.04,0:00:24.32,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٣ نحن نقص عليك أحسن القصص بما أوحينا إليك هذا القرآن\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}3. We relate to you ˹O Prophet˺ the best of stories\Nthrough Our revelation of this Quran,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:24.62,0:00:32.98,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}وإن كنت من قبله لمن الغافلين\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}though before this you were totally unaware ˹of\Nthem˺.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:33.28,0:00:40.52,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٤ إذ قال يوسف لأبيه يا أبت إني رأيت أحد عشر كوكبا\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}4. ˹Remember˺ when Joseph said to his father, "O my\Ndear father! Indeed I dreamt of eleven stars,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:40.82,0:00:45.22,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}والشمس والقمر رأيتهم لي ساجدين\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}and the sun, and the moon—I saw them prostrating to\Nme!"
Dialogue: 0,0:00:45.52,0:00:52.66,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٥ قال يا بني لا تقصص رؤياك على إخوتك فيكيدوا لك كيدا\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}5. He replied, "O my dear son! Do not relate your\Nvision to your brothers, or they will devise a plot\Nagainst you.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:52.96,0:00:59.22,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}إن الشيطان للإنسان عدو مبين\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}Surely Satan is a sworn enemy to humankind.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:59.52,0:01:06.94,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٦ وكذلك يجتبيك ربك ويعلمك من تأويل الأحاديث\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}6. And so will your Lord choose you ˹O Joseph˺, and\Nteach you the interpretation of dreams,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:07.24,0:01:16.94,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}ويتم نعمته عليك وعلى آل يعقوب كما أتمها على أبويك من قبل\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}and perfect His favour upon you and the descendants\Nof Jacob—˹just˺ as He once perfected it upon your\Nforefathers,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:17.24,0:01:24.18,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}كما أتمها على أبويك من قبل إبراهيم وإسحاق\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}of Jacob—˹just˺ as He once perfected it upon your\Nforefathers, Abraham and Isaac.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:24.48,0:01:28.42,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}إن ربك عليم حكيم\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}Surely your Lord is All-Knowing, All-Wise."
Dialogue: 0,0:01:28.72,0:01:37.24,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٧ لقد كان في يوسف وإخوته آيات للسائلين\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}7. Indeed, in the story of Joseph and his brothers\Nthere are lessons for all who ask.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:37.54,0:01:44.28,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٨ إذ قالوا ليوسف وأخوه أحب إلى أبينا منا ونحن عصبة\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}8. ˹Remember˺ when they said ˹to one another˺,\N"Surely Joseph and his brother ˹Benjamin˺ are more\Nbeloved to our father than we, even though we are a\Ngroup of so many.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:44.58,0:01:48.88,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}إن أبانا لفي ضلال مبين\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}Indeed, our father is clearly mistaken.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:49.18,0:01:55.34,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٩ أقتلوا يوسف أو اطرحوه أرضا يخل لكم وجه أبيكم\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}9. Kill Joseph or cast him out to some ˹distant˺\Nland so that our father's attention will be only\Nours,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:55.64,0:02:01.10,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}وتكونوا من بعده قوما صالحين\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}then after that you may ˹repent and˺ become\Nrighteous people!"
Dialogue: 0,0:02:01.40,0:02:09.22,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}١٠ قال قائل منهم لا تقتلوا يوسف وألقوه في غيابة الجب\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}10. One of them said, "Do not kill Joseph. But if\Nyou must do something, throw him into the bottom of\Na well
Dialogue: 0,0:02:09.52,0:02:18.26,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}يلتقطه بعض السيارة إن كنتم فاعلين\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}so perhaps he may be picked up by some travellers."
Dialogue: 0,0:02:18.56,0:02:27.56,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}١١ قالوا يا أبانا ما لك لا تأمنا على يوسف وإنا له لناصحون\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}11. They said, "O our father! Why do you not trust\Nus with Joseph, although we truly wish him well?
Dialogue: 0,0:02:27.86,0:02:35.02,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}١٢ أرسله معنا غدا يرتع ويلعب وإنا له لحافظون\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}12. Send him out with us tomorrow so that he may\Nenjoy himself and play. And we will really watch\Nover him."
Dialogue: 0,0:02:35.32,0:02:45.90,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}١٣ قال إني ليحزنني أن تذهبوا به وأخاف أن يأكله الذئب وأنتم عنه غافلون\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}13. He responded, "It would truly sadden me if you\Ntook him away with you, and I fear that a wolf may\Ndevour him while you are negligent of him."
Dialogue: 0,0:02:46.20,0:02:54.16,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}١٤ قالوا لئن أكله الذئب ونحن عصبة إنا إذا لخاسرون\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}14. They said, "If a wolf were to devour him,\Ndespite our strong group, then we would certainly be\Nlosers!"
Dialogue: 0,0:02:54.46,0:03:01.40,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}١٥ فلما ذهبوا به وأجمعوا أن يجعلوه في غيابة الجب\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}15. And so, when they took him away and decided to\Nthrow him into the bottom of the well,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:01.70,0:03:09.86,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}وأوحينا إليه لتنبئنهم بأمرهم هذا وهم لا يشعرون\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}We inspired him: "˹One day˺ you will remind them of\Nthis deed of theirs while they are unaware ˹of who\Nyou are˺."
Dialogue: 0,0:03:10.16,0:03:16.62,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}١٦ وجاءوا أباهم عشاء يبكون\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}16. Then they returned to their father in the\Nevening, weeping.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:16.92,0:03:26.68,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}١٧ قالوا يا أبانا إنا ذهبنا نستبق وتركنا يوسف عند متاعنا فأكله الذئب\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}17. They cried, "Our father! We went racing and left\NJoseph with our belongings, and a wolf devoured him!
Dialogue: 0,0:03:26.98,0:03:33.08,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}وما أنت بمؤمن لنا ولو كنا صادقين\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}But you will not believe us, no matter how truthful\Nwe are."
Dialogue: 0,0:03:33.38,0:03:46.68,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}١٨ وجاءوا على طميصه بدم كذب قال بل سولتنكم أنفسكم أمرا فصبر جميل\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}18. And they brought his shirt, stained with false\Nblood. He responded, "No! Your souls must have\Ntempted you to do something ˹evil˺. So ˹I can only\Nendure with˺ beautiful patience!
Dialogue: 0,0:03:46.98,0:03:51.42,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}والله المستعان على ما تصفون\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}It is Allah's help that I seek to bear your claims."
Dialogue: 0,0:03:51.72,0:04:02.50,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}١٩ وجاءت سيارة فأرسلوا واردهم فأدلى دلوه قال يا بشرى هذا غلام\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}19. And there came some travellers, and they sent\Ntheir water-boy who let down his bucket into the\Nwell. He cried out, "Oh, what a great find! Here is\Na boy!"
Dialogue: 0,0:04:02.80,0:04:09.16,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}وأسروه بضاعة والله عليم بما يعملون\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}And they took him secretly ˹to be sold˺ as\Nmerchandise, but Allah is All-Knowing of what they\Ndid.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:09.46,0:04:18.08,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٢٠ وشروه بثمن بخص دراهم معدودة وكانوا فيه من الزاهدين\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}20. They ˹later˺ sold him for a cheap price, just a\Nfew silver coins—only wanting to get rid of him.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:18.38,0:04:28.78,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٢١ وقال الذي اشتراه من مصر لمرأته أكرمي مثواه عسى أن ينفعنا أو نتخذه ولدا\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}21. The man from Egypt who bought him said to his\Nwife, "Take good care of him, perhaps he may be\Nuseful to us or we may adopt him as a son."
Dialogue: 0,0:04:29.08,0:04:37.70,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}وكذلك مكنا ليوسف في الأرض ولنعلمه من تأويل الأحاديث\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}This is how We established Joseph in the land, so\Nthat We might teach him the interpretation of\Ndreams.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:38.00,0:04:46.36,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}والله غالب على أمره ولكن أكثر الناس لا يعلمون\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}Allah's Will always prevails, but most people do not\Nknow.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:46.66,0:04:55.48,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٢٢ ولما بلغ أشده آتيناه حكما وعلما وكذلك نجزي المحسنين\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}22. And when he reached maturity, We gave him wisdom\Nand knowledge. This is how We reward the good-doers.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:55.78,0:05:04.36,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٢٣ وراودته التي هو في بيتها عن نفسه وغلقت الأبواب وقالت هيت لك\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}23. And the lady, in whose house he lived, tried to\Nseduce him. She locked the doors ˹firmly˺ and said,\N"Come to me!" He replied, "Allah is my refuge!
Dialogue: 0,0:05:04.66,0:05:13.02,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}قال معاذ الله إنه ربي أحسن مثوايا إنه لا يفلح الظالمون\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}It is ˹not right to betray˺ my master, who has taken\Ngood care of me. Indeed, the wrongdoers never\Nsucceed."
Dialogue: 0,0:05:13.32,0:05:32.02,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٢٤ ولقد همت به وهم بها لولا أرآ برهان ربه كذلك لنصرف عنه السوء والفحشاء إنه من عبادنا المخلصين\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}24. She advanced towards him, and he would have done\Nlikewise, had he not seen a sign from his Lord. This\Nis how We kept evil and indecency away from him, for\Nhe was truly one of Our chosen servants.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:32.32,0:05:40.68,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٢٥ واستبق الباب وقدت قميصه من دبر وألف يا سيدها لدى الباب\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}25. They raced for the door and she tore his shirt\Nfrom the back, only to find her husband at the door.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:40.98,0:05:50.68,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}قالت ما جزاء من أراد بأهلك سوءا إلا أن يسجن أو عذاب أليم\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}She cried, "What is the penalty for someone who\Ntried to violate your wife, except imprisonment or a\Npainful punishment?"
Dialogue: 0,0:05:50.98,0:06:05.90,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٢٦ قال هي راودتني عن نفسي وشهد شاهد من أهلها إن كان قميصه قد من قبل فصدقت وهو من الكاذبين\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}26. Joseph responded, "It was she who tried to\Nseduce me." And a witness from her own family\Ntestified: "If his shirt is torn from the front,\Nthen she has told the truth and he is a liar.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:06.20,0:06:13.92,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٢٧ وإن كان قميصه قد من دبر فكذبت وهو من الصادقين\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}27. But if it is torn from the back, then she has\Nlied and he is truthful."
Dialogue: 0,0:06:14.22,0:06:27.08,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٢٨ فلما رأى قميصه قد من دبر قال إنه من كيدكن عظيم\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}28. So when her husband saw that Joseph's shirt was\Ntorn from the back, he said ˹to her˺, "This must be\N˹an example˺ of the cunning of you ˹women˺! Indeed,\Nyour cunning is so shrewd!
Dialogue: 0,0:06:27.38,0:06:36.68,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٢٩ يوسف أعرض عن هذا واستغفرين ذنبك إنك كنت من الخاطئين\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}29. O Joseph! Forget about this. And you ˹O wife˺!\NSeek forgiveness for your sin. It certainly has been\Nyour fault."
Dialogue: 0,0:06:36.98,0:06:47.02,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٣٠ وقال نسوة في المدينة امرأة العزيز تراود فتاها عن نفسه قد شغفها حبا\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}30. Some women of the city gossiped, "The Chief\NMinister's wife is trying to seduce her slave-boy.\NLove for him has plagued her heart.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:47.32,0:06:51.68,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}إنا لنراها في ضلال مبين\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}Some women of the city gossiped, "The Chief\NMinister's wife is trying to seduce her slave-boy.\NLove for him has plagued her heart. Indeed, we see\Nthat she is clearly mistaken."
Dialogue: 0,0:06:51.98,0:07:07.68,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٣١ فلما سمعت بمكرهن أرسلت إليهن وأعتدت لهن متكأا وآتت كل واحدة منهن سكينا وقالت خرج عليهم\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}31. When she heard about their gossip, she invited\Nthem and set a banquet for them. She gave each one a\Nknife, then said to Joseph, "Come out before them."\NWhen they saw him,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:07.98,0:07:21.96,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}فلما رأينه أكبرنه وقطعن أيديهن وقلن حاش لله ما هذا بشرا إن هذا إلا ملك كريم\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}they were so stunned ˹by his beauty˺ that they cut\Ntheir hands, and exclaimed, "Good God! This cannot\Nbe human; this must be a noble angel!"
Dialogue: 0,0:07:22.26,0:07:31.42,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٣٢ قالت فذلكن الذي لمتنني فيه ولقد راوته عن نفسه فاستعصم\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}32. She said, "This is the one for whose love you\Ncriticized me! I did try to seduce him but he\N˹firmly˺ refused.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:31.72,0:07:39.20,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}ولئن لم يفعل ما آمره ليسجنن وليكون من الصاغرين\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}And if he does not do what I order him to, he will\Ncertainly be imprisoned and ˹fully˺ disgraced."
Dialogue: 0,0:07:39.50,0:07:52.66,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٣٣ قال رب السجن أحب إلي مما يدعونني إليه وإلا تصرف عني كيدهن أصب إليهن وأكون من الجاهلين\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}33. He said, "My Lord, prison is more to my liking\Nthan that to which they invite me. And if You do not\Navert from me their plan, I might incline toward\Nthem and ˹thus˺ be of the ignorant."
Dialogue: 0,0:07:52.96,0:08:00.62,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٣٤ فاستجاب له ربه فصرف عنه كيدهن إنه هو السميع العليم\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}34. So his Lord responded to him, turning their\Ncunning away from him. Surely He is the All-Hearing,\NAll-Knowing.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:00.92,0:08:08.80,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٣٥ ثم بدى لهم من بعد ما رأوا الآيات ليسجننه حتى حين\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}35. And so it occurred to those in charge, despite\Nseeing all the proofs ˹of his innocence˺, that he\Nshould be imprisoned for a while.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:09.10,0:08:16.16,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٣٦ ودخل معه السجن فتيان قال أحدهما إني أراني أعصر خمرا\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}36. And two other servants went to jail with Joseph.\NOne of them said, "I dreamt I was pressing wine."\NThe other said,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:16.46,0:08:23.98,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}وقال الآخر إني أراني أحمل فوق رأسي خبزا تأكل الطير منه\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}"I dreamt I was carrying ˹some˺ bread on my head,\Nfrom which birds were eating." ˹Then both said,˺\N"Tell us their interpretation,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:24.28,0:08:29.82,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}نبئنا بتأويله إنا نراك من المحسنين\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}for we surely see you as one of the good-doers."
Dialogue: 0,0:08:30.12,0:08:44.24,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٣٧ قال لا يأتيكما طعام ترزقانه إلا نبأتكما بتأويله قبل أن يأتيكما ذلكما مما علمني ربي\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}37. Joseph replied, "I can even tell you what kind\Nof meal you will be served before you receive it.\NThis ˹knowledge˺ is from what my Lord has taught me.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:44.54,0:08:53.22,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}إني تركت ملة قوم لا يؤمنون بالله وهم بالآخرة هم كافرون\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}I have shunned the faith of a people who disbelieve\Nin Allah and deny the Hereafter.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:53.52,0:09:00.66,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٣٨ واتبعت ملة آبائي إبراهيم وإسحاق ويعقوب\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}38. I follow the faith of my fathers: Abraham,\NIsaac,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:00.96,0:09:10.90,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}ما كان لنا أن نشرك بالله من شيء ذلك من فضل الله علينا وعلى الناس\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}and Jacob. It is not ˹right˺ for us to associate\Nanything with Allah ˹in worship˺. This is part of\NAllah's grace upon us and humanity,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:11.20,0:09:15.62,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}ولكن أكثر الناس لا يشترون\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}but most people are not grateful.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:15.92,0:09:24.68,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٣٩ يا صاحبي السجن أأرباب متفرقون خير أم الله الواحد القهار\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}39. O my fellow-prisoners! Which is far better: many\Ndifferent lords or Allah—the One, the Supreme?
Dialogue: 0,0:09:24.98,0:09:44.40,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٤٠ ما تعبدون من دونه إلا أسماء سميتموها أنتم وآباؤكم ما أنزل الله بها من سلطان\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}40. Whatever ˹idols˺ you worship instead of Him are\Nmere names which you and your forefathers have made\Nup—a practice Allah has never authorized.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:44.70,0:09:57.50,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}إن الحكم إلا لله أمر أن لا تعبدوا إلا إياه ذلك الدين القيم ولكن أكثر الناس لا يعلمون\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}It is only Allah Who decides. He has commanded that\Nyou worship none but Him. That is the upright faith,\Nbut most people do not know.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:57.80,0:10:03.84,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٤١ يا صاحبي السجن أما أحدكما فيسقي ربه خمرا\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}41. "O my fellow-prisoners! ˹The first˺ one of you\Nwill serve wine to his master,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:04.14,0:10:13.20,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}وأما الآخر فيسلب فتأكل الطير من رأسه قضي الأمر الذي فيه تستفتيان\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}and the other will be crucified and the birds will\Neat from his head. The matter about which you\Ninquired has been decided."
Dialogue: 0,0:10:13.50,0:10:28.46,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٤٢ وقال للذي ظن أنه ناج منهم اذكرني عند ربك فأنساه الشيطان ذكر ربه فلبث في السجن بطع سنين\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}42. Then he said to the one he knew would survive,\N"Mention me in the presence of your master." But\NSatan made him forget to mention Joseph to his\Nmaster, so he remained in prison for several years.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:28.76,0:10:37.26,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٤٣ وقال الملك إني أرى سبع بقرات سمان يأكلهن سبع عجاف\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}43. And ˹one day˺ the King said, "I dreamt of seven\Nfat cows eaten up by seven skinny ones;
Dialogue: 0,0:10:37.56,0:10:42.38,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}وسبع سنبلات خضر وأخر يابسات\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}and seven green ears of grain and ˹seven˺ others\Ndry.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:42.68,0:10:50.12,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}يا أيها الملأ أفتوني في رؤياي إن كنتم للرؤيا تعبرون\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}O chiefs! Tell me the meaning of my dream if you can\Ninterpret dreams."
Dialogue: 0,0:10:50.42,0:10:57.10,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٤٤ قالوا أضغاث أحلام وما نحن بتأويل الأحلام بعالمين\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}44. They replied, "These are confused visions and we\Ndo not know the interpretation of such dreams."
Dialogue: 0,0:10:57.40,0:11:06.54,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٤٥ وقال الذين جاء منهما وادكر بعد أمة أنا أنبئكم بتأويله فأرسنون\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}45. ˹Finally,˺ the surviving ex-prisoner remembered\N˹Joseph˺ after a long time and said, "I will tell\Nyou its interpretation, so send me forth ˹to\NJoseph˺."
Dialogue: 0,0:11:06.84,0:11:15.42,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٤٦ يوسف أيها الصديق أفتنا في سبع بقرات سمان يأكلهن سبع عجاف\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}46. ˹He said,˺ "Joseph, O man of truth! Interpret\Nfor us ˹the dream of˺ seven fat cows eaten up by\Nseven skinny ones;
Dialogue: 0,0:11:15.72,0:11:25.46,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}وسبع سنبلات خضر وأخر يابسات لعلي أرجع إلى الناس لعلهم يعلمون\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}and seven green ears of grain and ˹seven˺ others\Ndry, so that I may return to the people and let them\Nknow."
Dialogue: 0,0:11:25.76,0:11:36.14,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٤٧ قال تزرعون سبع سنين دأبا فما حصدتم فذروه في سنبله إلا قليلا مما تأكلون\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}47. Joseph replied, "You will plant ˹grain˺ for\Nseven consecutive years, leaving in the ear whatever\Nyou will harvest, except for the little you will\Neat.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:36.44,0:11:49.28,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٤٨ ثم يأتي من بعد ذلك سبع شداد يأكل ما قدمتم لهن إلا قليلا مما تحصنون\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}48. Then after that will come seven years of great\Nhardship which will consume whatever you have saved,\Nexcept the little you will store ˹for seed˺.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:49.58,0:11:57.26,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٤٩ ثم يأتي من بعد ذلك عام فيه يغاث الناس وفيه يعصرون\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}49. Then after that will come a year in which people\Nwill receive abundant rain and they will press ˹oil\Nand wine˺."
Dialogue: 0,0:11:57.56,0:12:10.40,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٥٠ وقال الملك أتوني به فلما جاءه الرسول قال ارجع إلى ربك فاسألهما بال النسوة التي قطعن أيديهن\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}50. The King ˹then˺ said, "Bring him to me." When\Nthe messenger came to him, Joseph said, "Go back to\Nyour master and ask him about the case of the women\Nwho cut their hands.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:10.70,0:12:14.40,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}إن ربي بكيدهن عليم\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}Surely my Lord has ˹full˺ knowledge of their\Ncunning."
Dialogue: 0,0:12:14.70,0:12:24.26,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٥١ قال ما خطبكن إذ راودتن يوسف عن نفسه قلن حاش لله ما علمنا عليه من سوء\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}51. The King asked ˹the women˺, "What did you get\Nwhen you tried to seduce Joseph?" They replied,\N"Allah forbid! We know nothing indecent about him."\NThen the Chief Minister's wife admitted,
Dialogue: 0,0:12:24.56,0:12:34.26,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}قالت امرأة العزيز الآن حصحص الحق أنا راودته عن نفسه وإنه لمن الصادقين\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}"Now the truth has come to light. It was I who tried\Nto seduce him, and he is surely truthful.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:35.44,0:12:44.70,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٥٢ ذلك ليعلم أني لم أخنه بالغيب وأن الله لا يهدي كيد الخائنين\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}52. From this, Joseph should know that I did not\Nspeak dishonestly about him in his absence, for\NAllah certainly does not guide the scheming of the\Ndishonest.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:45.00,0:12:58.54,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٥٣ وما أبرئ نفسي إن النفس لأمارة بالسوء إلا ما رحم ربي إن ربي غفور رحيم\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}53. And I do not seek to free myself from blame, for\Nindeed the soul is ever inclined to evil, except\Nthose shown mercy by my Lord. Surely my Lord is All-\NForgiving, Most Merciful."
Dialogue: 0,0:12:58.84,0:13:09.54,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٥٤ وقال الملك أتوني به أستخلصه لنفسي فلما كلمه قال إنك اليوم لدينا مكين أمين\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}54. The King said, "Bring him to me. I will employ\Nhim exclusively in my service." And when Joseph\Nspoke to him, the King said, "Today you are highly\Nesteemed and fully trusted by us."
Dialogue: 0,0:13:10.70,0:13:15.54,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٥٥ قال جعلني على خزائن الأرض إني حفيظ عليم\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}55. Joseph proposed, "Put me in charge of the store-\Nhouses of the land, for I am truly reliable and\Nadept."
Dialogue: 0,0:13:15.84,0:13:22.54,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٥٦ وكذلك مكنا ليوسف في الأرض يتبوأ منها حيث يشاء\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}56. This is how We established Joseph in the land to\Nsettle wherever he pleased.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:23.68,0:13:26.54,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}نصيب برحمتنا من نشاء\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}We shower Our mercy on whoever We will,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:27.74,0:13:29.54,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}ولا نضيع أجر المحسنين\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}and We never discount the reward of the good-doers.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:30.98,0:13:36.54,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٥٧ ولأجر الآخرة خير للذين آمنوا وكانوا يتقون\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}57. And the reward of the Hereafter is far better\Nfor those who are faithful and are mindful ˹of\NAllah˺.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:36.84,0:13:44.54,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٥٨ وجاء إخوة يوسف فدخلوا عليه فعرفهم وهم له منكرون\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}58. And Joseph's brothers came and entered his\Npresence. He recognized them but they were unaware\Nof who he really was.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:45.90,0:13:52.60,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٥٩ ولما جهزهم بجهازهم قال أتوني بأخ لكم من أبيكم\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}59. When he had provided them with their supplies,\Nhe demanded, "Bring me your brother on your father's\Nside.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:52.90,0:13:57.54,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}ألا ترون أني أوف الكيل وأنا خير المنزنين\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}Do you not see that I give full measure and I am the\Nbest of hosts?
Dialogue: 0,0:13:59.00,0:14:03.54,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٦٠ فإن لم تأتوني به فلا كيل لكم عندي ولا تقربون\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}60. But if you do not bring him to me ˹next time˺, I\Nwill have no grain for you, nor will you ever come\Nclose to me again."
Dialogue: 0,0:14:03.84,0:14:09.54,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٦١ قالوا سنراود عنه أباه وإنا لفاعلون\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}61. They promised, "We will try to convince his\Nfather to let him come. We will certainly do ˹our\Nbest˺."
Dialogue: 0,0:14:10.78,0:14:16.54,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٦٢ وقال لفتيانه اجعلوا بضاعتهم في رحالهم لعلهم يعرفونها\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}62. Joseph ordered his servants to put his brothers'\Nmoney back into their saddlebags so that they would
Dialogue: 0,0:14:17.88,0:14:24.54,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}إذا انقلبوا إلى أهلهم لعلهم يرجعون\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}find it when they returned to their family and\Nperhaps they would come back.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:25.46,0:14:31.66,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٦٣ فلما رجعوا إلى أبيهم قالوا يا أبانا منع منا الكيل\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}63. When Joseph's brothers returned to their father,\Nthey pleaded, "O our father! We have been denied\N˹further˺ supplies. So send our brother with us so\Nthat we may receive our measure,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:31.96,0:14:36.66,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}فأرسل معنا أخانا نكتل وإنا له لحافظون\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}and we will definitely watch over him."
Dialogue: 0,0:14:37.60,0:14:43.66,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٦٤ قال هل آمنكم عليه إلا كما أمنتكم على أخيه من قبل\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}64. He responded, "Should I trust you with him as I\Nonce trusted you with his brother ˹Joseph˺? But\N˹only˺ Allah is the best Protector,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:44.56,0:14:50.66,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}فالله خير حافظا وهو أرحم الراحمين\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}and He is the Most Merciful of the merciful."
Dialogue: 0,0:14:50.96,0:14:57.60,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٦٥ ولما فتحوا متاعهم وجدوا بضاعتهم ردت إليهم\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}65. When they opened their bags, they discovered\Nthat their money had been returned to them.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:57.90,0:15:04.04,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}قالوا يا أبانا ما نبغي هذه بضاعتنا ردت إلينا\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}They argued, "O our father! What more can we ask\Nfor? Here is our money, fully returned to us. Now we\Ncan buy more food for our family.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:04.34,0:15:09.48,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}ونمير أهلنا ونحفظ أخانا ونزداد كيل بعير\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}We will watch over our brother, and obtain an extra\Ncamel-load of grain. That load can be easily\Nsecured."
Dialogue: 0,0:15:09.78,0:15:11.66,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}ذلك كيل يسير\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}When they opened their bags, they discovered that\Ntheir money had been returned to them. They argued,\N"O our father! What more can we ask for? Here is our\Nmoney, fully returned to us. Now we can buy more\Nfood for our family. We will watch over our brother,\Nand obtain an extra camel-load of grain. That load\Ncan be easily secured."
Dialogue: 0,0:15:11.96,0:15:18.98,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٦٦ قال لن أرسله معكم حتى تؤتون موثقا من الله\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}66. Jacob insisted, "I will not send him with you\Nuntil you give me a solemn oath by Allah that you\Nwill certainly bring him back to me, unless you are\Ntotally overpowered." Then after they had given him\Ntheir oaths, he concluded, "Allah
Dialogue: 0,0:15:19.28,0:15:23.44,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}لتأتنني به إلا أن يحاط بكم\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}is
Dialogue: 0,0:15:23.74,0:15:30.70,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}فلما آتوه موثقهم قال الله على ما نقول وكيل\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}a Witness to what we have said."
Dialogue: 0,0:15:31.00,0:15:35.72,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٦٧ وقال يا بني لا تدخلوا من باب واحد\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}67. He then instructed ˹them˺, "O my sons! Do not\Nenter ˹the city˺ all through one gate,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:36.02,0:15:39.70,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}وادخلوا من أبواب متفرقة\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}but through separate gates.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:40.00,0:15:44.94,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}وما أغني عنكم من الله من شيء\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}I cannot help you against ˹what is destined by˺\NAllah in the least.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:45.24,0:15:52.72,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}إن الحكم إلا لله عليه توكلت وعليه فليتوكل المتوكلون\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}It is only Allah Who decides. In Him I put my trust.\NAnd in Him let the faithful put their trust."
Dialogue: 0,0:15:53.02,0:16:06.78,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٦٨ ولما دخلوا من حيث أمرهم أبوهم ما كان يغني عنهم من الله من شيء\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}68. Then when they entered as their father had\Ninstructed them, this did not help them against ˹the\NWill of˺ Allah whatsoever.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:07.08,0:16:10.94,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}إلا حاجة في نفس يعقوب قضاها\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}It was just a desire in Jacob's heart which he\Nsatisfied.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:11.24,0:16:19.50,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}وإنه لذو علم لما علمناه ولكن أكثر الناس لا يعلمون\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}He was truly blessed with ˹great˺ knowledge because\Nof what We had taught him, but most people have no\Nknowledge.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:19.80,0:16:24.82,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٦٩ ولما دخلوا على يوسف آوى إليه أخاه\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}69. When they entered Joseph's presence, he called\Nhis brother ˹Benjamin˺ aside, and confided ˹to him˺,\N"I am indeed your brother ˹Joseph˺!
Dialogue: 0,0:16:25.12,0:16:31.42,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}قال إني أنا أخوك فلا تبتئس بما كانوا يعملون\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}So do not feel distressed about what they have been\Ndoing."
Dialogue: 0,0:16:31.72,0:16:37.50,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٧٠ فلما جهزهم بجهازهم جعل السقاية في رحل أخيه\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}70. When Joseph had provided them with supplies, he\Nslipped the royal cup into his brother's bag.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:37.80,0:16:44.34,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}ثم أذن مؤذن أيتها العير إنكم لسارقون\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}Then a herald cried, "O people of the caravan! You\Nmust be thieves!"
Dialogue: 0,0:16:44.64,0:16:48.98,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٧١ قالوا وأقبلوا عليهم ماذا تفقدون\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}71. They asked, turning back, "What have you lost?"
Dialogue: 0,0:16:49.28,0:16:57.90,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٧٢ قالوا نفقد صواع الملك ولمن جاء به حمل بعير وأنا به زعيم\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}72. The herald ˹along with the guards˺ replied, "We\Nhave lost the King's measuring cup. And whoever\Nbrings it will be awarded a camel-load ˹of grain˺. I\Nguarantee it."
Dialogue: 0,0:16:58.20,0:17:06.42,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٧٣ قالوا تالله لقد علمتم ما جئنا لنفسد في الأرض وما كنا سارقين\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}73. Joseph's brothers replied, "By Allah! You know\Nwell that we did not come to cause trouble in the\Nland, nor are we thieves."
Dialogue: 0,0:17:06.72,0:17:12.20,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٧٤ قالوا فما جزاؤه إن كنتم كاذبين\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}74. Joseph's men asked, "What should be the price\Nfor theft, if you are lying?"
Dialogue: 0,0:17:12.50,0:17:23.12,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٧٥ قالوا جزاؤه من وجد في رحله فهو جزاؤه كذلك نجزي الظالمين\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}75. Joseph's brothers responded, "The price will be\N˹the enslavement of˺ the one in whose bag the cup is\Nfound. That is how we punish the wrongdoers."
Dialogue: 0,0:17:23.42,0:17:32.04,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٧٦ فبدأ بأوعيتهم قبل وعاء أخيه ثم استخرجها من وعاء\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}76. Joseph began searching their bags before that of\Nhis brother ˹Benjamin˺, then brought it out of\NBenjamin's bag.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:32.34,0:17:39.32,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}أخيه كذلك كدنا ليوسف ما كان ليأخذ أخاه في دين الملك\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}This is how We inspired Joseph to plan. He could not\Nhave taken his brother under the King's law,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:39.62,0:17:48.24,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}إلا أن يشاء الله نرفع درجات من نشاء\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}but Allah had so willed. We elevate in rank whoever\NWe will.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:48.54,0:17:53.24,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}وفوق كل ذي علم عليم\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}But above those ranking in knowledge is the One All-\NKnowing.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:53.54,0:18:03.22,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٧٧ قالوا إن يسرق فقد سرق أخ له من قبل فأسرها يوسف في نفسه ولم يبدها لهم\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}77. ˹To distance themselves,˺ Joseph's brothers\Nargued, "If he has stolen, so did his ˹full˺ brother\Nbefore." But Joseph suppressed his outrage—revealing\Nnothing to them—and said ˹to himself˺,
Dialogue: 0,0:18:03.52,0:18:10.12,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}قال أنتم شر مكانا والله أعلم بما تصفون\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}"You are in such an evil position, and Allah knows\Nbest ˹the truth of˺ what you claim."
Dialogue: 0,0:18:10.42,0:18:22.02,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٧٨ قالوا يا أيها العزيز إن له أبا شيخا كبيرا فخذ أحدنا مكانه إنا نراك من المحسنين\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}78. They appealed, "O Chief Minister! He has a very\Nold father, so take one of us instead. We surely see\Nyou as one of the good-doers."
Dialogue: 0,0:18:22.32,0:18:32.02,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٧٩ قال معاذ الله أن نأخذ إلا من وجدنا متاعنا عنده إنا إذا لظالمون\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}79. Joseph responded, "Allah forbid that we should\Ntake other than the one with whom we found our\Nproperty. Otherwise, we would surely be unjust."
Dialogue: 0,0:18:32.92,0:18:36.82,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٨٠ فلما استيئسوا منه خلصوا نجيا\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}80. When they lost all hope in him, they spoke\Nprivately.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:37.12,0:18:51.68,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}قال كبيرهم ألم تعلموا أن أباكم قد أخذ عليكم موثقا من الله\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}The eldest of them said, "Do you not know that your\Nfather had taken a solemn oath by Allah from you,\Nnor how you failed him regarding Joseph before? So I\Nam not leaving this land until my father allows me\Nto, or Allah decides for me.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:51.98,0:19:02.82,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}ومن قبل ما فردتم في يوسف فلن أبرح الأرض حتى يأذن لي أبي أو يحكم الله لي وهو خير الحاكمين\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}For He is the Best of Judges.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:03.12,0:19:17.12,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٨١ ارجعوا إلى أبيكم فقولوا يا أبانا إن ابنك سرق وما شهدنا إلا بما علمنا وما كنا للغيب حافظين\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}81. Return to your father and say, 'O our father!\NYour son committed theft. We testify only to what we\Nknow. We could not guard against the unforeseen.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:17.42,0:19:26.42,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٨٢ واسأل القرية التي كنا فيها والعير التي أقبلنا فيها وإنا لصادقون\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}82. Ask ˹the people of˺ the land where we were and\Nthe caravan we travelled with. We are certainly\Ntelling the truth.'"
Dialogue: 0,0:19:26.72,0:19:33.16,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٨٣ قال بل سولت لكم أنفسكم أمرا فصبر جميل\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}83. He cried, "No! Your souls must have tempted you\Nto do something ˹evil˺. So ˹I am left with nothing\Nbut˺ beautiful patience!
Dialogue: 0,0:19:33.46,0:19:41.60,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}عسى الله أن يأتيني بهم جميعا إنه هو العليم الحكيم\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}I trust Allah will return them all to me. Surely He\N˹alone˺ is the All-Knowing, All-Wise."
Dialogue: 0,0:19:41.90,0:19:50.36,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٨٤ وتولى عنهم وقال يا أسفى على يوسف وبيضت عيناه من الحزن فهو كظيم\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}84. He turned away from them, lamenting, "Alas, poor\NJoseph!" And his eyes turned white out of the grief\Nhe suppressed.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:50.66,0:19:58.50,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٨٥ قالوا تالله تفتأ تذكر يوسف حتى تكون حرضا أو تكون من الهالكين\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}85. They said, "By Allah! You will not cease to\Nremember Joseph until you lose your health or ˹even˺\Nyour life."
Dialogue: 0,0:19:58.80,0:20:18.60,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٨٦ قال إنما أشكوا بثي وحزني إلى الله وأعلم من الله ما لا تعلمون\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}86. He replied, "I complain of my anguish and sorrow\Nonly to Allah, and I know from Allah what you do not\Nknow.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:18.90,0:20:27.10,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٨٧ يا بني يذهبوا فتحسسوا من يوسف وأخيه ولا تيأسوا من روح الله\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}87. O my sons! Go and search ˹diligently˺ for Joseph\Nand his brother. And do not lose hope in the mercy\Nof Allah,
Dialogue: 0,0:20:27.40,0:20:33.56,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}إنه لا ييأس من روح الله إلا القوم الكافرون\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}for no one loses hope in Allah's mercy except those\Nwith no faith."
Dialogue: 0,0:20:33.86,0:20:47.32,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٨٨ فلما دخلوا عليه قالوا يا أيها العزيز مسلا وأهلنا الضر وجئنا ببضاعة مزجات\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}88. When they entered Joseph's presence, they\Npleaded, "O Chief Minister! We and our family have\Nbeen touched with hardship, and we have brought only\Na few worthless coins,
Dialogue: 0,0:20:47.62,0:20:55.06,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}فأوفلنا الكيل وتصدق علينا إن الله يجزي المتصدقين\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}but ˹please˺ give us our supplies in full and be\Ncharitable to us. Indeed, Allah rewards the\Ncharitable."
Dialogue: 0,0:20:55.36,0:21:02.34,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٨٩ قال هل علمتم ما فعلتم بيوسف وأخيه إذ أنتم جاهلون\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}89. He asked, "Do you remember what you did to\NJoseph and his brother in your ignorance?"
Dialogue: 0,0:21:02.64,0:21:11.50,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٩٠ قالوا أئنك لأنت يوسف قال أنا يوسف وهذا أخي قد من الله علينا\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}90. They replied ˹in shock˺, "Are you really\NJoseph?" He said, "I am Joseph, and here is my\Nbrother ˹Benjamin˺! Allah has truly been gracious to\Nus.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:11.80,0:21:19.34,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}إنه من يتق ويصبر فإن الله لا يضيع عجر المحسنين\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}Surely whoever is mindful ˹of Allah˺ and patient,\Nthen certainly Allah never discounts the reward of\Nthe good-doers."
Dialogue: 0,0:21:19.64,0:21:26.56,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٩١ قالوا تالله لقد آثرك الله علينا وإن كنا لخاطئين\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}91. They admitted, "By Allah! Allah has truly\Npreferred you over us, and we have surely been\Nsinful."
Dialogue: 0,0:21:26.86,0:21:34.62,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٩٢ قال لا تثريب عليكم اليوم يغفر الله لكم وهو أرحم الراحمين\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}92. Joseph said, "There is no blame on you today.\NMay Allah forgive you! He is the Most Merciful of\Nthe merciful!
Dialogue: 0,0:21:34.92,0:21:41.56,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٩٣ اذهبوا بقميصي هذا فألقوه على وجه أبي يأتي بصيرا\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}93. Go with this shirt of mine and cast it over my\Nfather's face, and he will regain his sight.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:41.86,0:21:47.56,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}يأتي بصيرا وأتوني بأهلكم أجمعين\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}Then come back to me with your whole family."
Dialogue: 0,0:21:47.86,0:21:58.02,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٩٤ ولما فصلت العير قال أبوهم إني لأجد ريح يوسف لولا أن تفندون\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}94. When the caravan departed ˹from Egypt˺, their\Nfather said ˹to those around him˺, "You may think I\Nam senile, but I certainly sense the smell of\NJoseph."
Dialogue: 0,0:21:58.32,0:22:02.56,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٩٥ قالوا تالله إنك لفي طلالك القديم\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}95. They replied, "By Allah! You are definitely\Nstill in your old delusion."
Dialogue: 0,0:22:02.86,0:22:10.90,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٩٦ فلما أن جاء البشير ألقاه على وجهه فارتد بصيرا\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}96. But when the bearer of the good news arrived, he\Ncast the shirt over Jacob's face, so he regained his\Nsight.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:11.20,0:22:17.56,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}قال ألم أقل لكم إني أعلم من الله ما لا تعلمون\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}Jacob then said ˹to his children˺, "Did I not tell\Nyou that I truly know from Allah what you do not\Nknow?"
Dialogue: 0,0:22:18.40,0:22:24.56,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٩٧ قالوا يا أبان استغفر لنا ذنوبنا إنا كنا خاطئين\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}97. They begged, "O our father! Pray for the\Nforgiveness of our sins. We have certainly been\Nsinful."
Dialogue: 0,0:22:24.86,0:22:32.56,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٩٨ قال سوف أستغفر لكم ربي إنه هو الغفور الرحيم\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}98. He said, "I will pray to my Lord for your\Nforgiveness. He ˹alone˺ is indeed the All-Forgiving,\NMost Merciful."
Dialogue: 0,0:22:33.44,0:22:43.56,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}٩٩ فلما دخلوا على يوسف آوى إليه أبويه وقال دخلوا مصر إن شاء الله آمنين\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}99. When they entered Joseph's presence, he received\Nhis parents ˹graciously˺ and said, "Enter Egypt,\NAllah willing, in security."
Dialogue: 0,0:22:43.86,0:22:48.56,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}١٠٠ ورفع أبويه على العرش وخروا له سجدا\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}100. Then he raised his parents to the throne, and\Nthey all fell down in prostration to Joseph,
Dialogue: 0,0:22:49.74,0:22:56.56,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}وقال يا أبت هذا تأويل رؤياي من قبل قد جعلها ربي حقا\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}who then said, "O my dear father! This is the\Ninterpretation of my old dream. My Lord has made it\Ncome true.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:57.58,0:23:06.56,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}وقد أحسن بي إذ أخرجني من السجن وجاء بكم من البدو من بعد أن نزغ الشيطان\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}He was truly kind to me when He freed me from\Nprison, and brought you all from the desert after\NSatan had ignited rivalry between me and my\Nsiblings.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:06.86,0:23:20.56,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}من بعد أن نزغ الشيطان بيني وبين إخوتي إن ربي لطيف لما يشاء إنه هو العليم الحكيم\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}and brought you all from the desert after Satan had\Nignited rivalry between me and my siblings. Indeed\Nmy Lord is subtle in fulfilling what He wills.\NSurely He ˹alone˺ is the All-Knowing, All-Wise."
Dialogue: 0,0:23:21.88,0:23:28.56,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}١٠١ ربي قد آتيتني من الملك وعلمتني من تأويل الأحاديث\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}101. "My Lord! You have surely granted me authority\Nand taught me the interpretation of dreams. ˹O˺\NOriginator of the heavens and the earth!
Dialogue: 0,0:23:28.86,0:23:35.56,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}فاطر السماوات والأرض أنت ولي في الدنيا والآخرة\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}You are my Guardian in this world and the Hereafter.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:36.54,0:23:39.56,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}أنت ولي في الدنيا والآخرة\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}You are my Guardian in this world and the Hereafter.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:40.64,0:23:44.56,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}توفني مسلما وألحقني بالصالحين\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}Allow me to die as one who submits and join me with\Nthe righteous."
Dialogue: 0,0:23:45.98,0:23:50.56,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}١٠٢ ذلك من أنباء الغيب نوحيه إليك\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}102. That is from the stories of the unseen which We\Nreveal to you ˹O Prophet˺.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:51.66,0:23:56.56,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}وما كنت لديهم إذ أجمعوا أمرهم وهم يمكرون\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}You were not present when they ˹all˺ made up their\Nminds, and when they plotted ˹against Joseph˺.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:56.86,0:24:02.82,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}١٠٣ وما أكثر الناس ولو حرصت بمؤمنين\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}103. And most people will not believe—no matter how\Nkeen you are—
Dialogue: 0,0:24:03.12,0:24:08.56,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}١٠٤ وما تسألهم عليه من أجر إنه إلا ذكر للعالمين\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}104. even though you are not asking them for a\Nreward for this ˹Quran˺. It is only a reminder to\Nthe whole world.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:09.64,0:24:17.56,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}١٠٥ وكأي من آية في السماوات والأرض يمرون عليها وهم عنها معرضون\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}105. How many signs in the heavens and the earth do\Nthey pass by with indifference!
Dialogue: 0,0:24:18.54,0:24:23.96,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}١٠٦ وما يؤمن أكثرهم بالله إلا وهم مشركون\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}106. And most of them do not believe in Allah\Nwithout associating others with Him ˹in worship˺.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:24.26,0:24:29.30,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}١٠٧ أفأمنوا أن تأتيهم راشية من عذاب الله\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}107. Do they feel secure that an overwhelming\Ntorment from Allah will not overtake them,
Dialogue: 0,0:24:29.60,0:24:33.96,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}أو تأتيهم الساعة بغتة وهم لا يشعرون\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}or that the Hour will not take them by surprise when\Nthey least expect ˹it˺?
Dialogue: 0,0:24:34.26,0:24:41.42,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}١٠٨ قل هذه سبيلي أدعو إلى الله على بصيرة أنا ومن اتبعني\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}108. Say, ˹O Prophet,˺ "This is my way. I invite to\NAllah with insight—I and those who follow me.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:41.72,0:24:58.12,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}وسبحان الله وسبحان الله وما أنا من المشركين\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}I invite to Allah with insight—I and those who\Nfollow me. Glory be to Allah, and I am not one of\Nthe polytheists."
Dialogue: 0,0:24:58.42,0:25:06.82,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}١٠٩ وما أرسلنا من قبلك إلا رجالا نوحي إليهم من أهل القرى\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}109. We only sent before you ˹O Prophet˺ men\Ninspired by Us from among the people of each\Nsociety.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:07.12,0:25:13.46,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}أفلم يسيروا في الأرض فينظروا كيف كان عاقبة الذين من قبلهم\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}Have the deniers not travelled through the land to\Nsee what was the end of those ˹destroyed˺ before\Nthem? And surely the ˹eternal˺ Home of the Hereafter
Dialogue: 0,0:25:13.76,0:25:19.46,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}ولدار الآخرة خير للذين اتقوا أفلا تعقلون\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}is far better for those mindful ˹of Allah˺. Will you\Nnot then understand?
Dialogue: 0,0:25:19.76,0:25:26.80,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}١١٠ حتى إذا استيأس الرسل وظنوا أنهم قد كذبوا\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}110. And when the messengers despaired and their\Npeople thought the messengers had been denied help,
Dialogue: 0,0:25:27.10,0:25:29.46,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}جاءهم نصرنا\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}Our help came to them ˹at last˺.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:29.76,0:25:34.46,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}جاءهم نصرنا فنجي من نشاء\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}Our help came to them ˹at last˺. We then saved\Nwhoever We willed,
Dialogue: 0,0:25:35.60,0:25:39.46,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}ولا يرد بأسنا عن القوم المجرمين\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}and Our punishment is never averted from the wicked\Npeople.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:39.76,0:25:45.78,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}١١١ لقد كان في قصصهم عبرة لأولي الألباب\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}111. In their stories there is truly a lesson for\Npeople of reason.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:46.08,0:25:49.32,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}ما كان حديثا يفترى\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}This message cannot be a fabrication,
Dialogue: 0,0:25:49.62,0:25:53.40,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}ولكن تصديق الذي بين يديه\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}rather ˹it is˺ a confirmation of previous\Nrevelation,
Dialogue: 0,0:25:53.70,0:26:01.56,Default,,0,0,0,,{\fnTraditional Arabic\fs56}وتفصيل كل شيء وهدى ورحمة لقوم يؤمنون\N\N{\fnTimes New Roman\fs48}a detailed explanation of all things, a guide, and a\Nmercy for people of faith.
